Engine Blueprint
1) Define what “engine” owns vs what the “app” owns

Engine responsibilities (your focus):
	•	Validate assignment key for submissions (accept/reject).
	•	Build a representation of each submission:
	•	concatenate source files
	•	strip comments
	•	tokenize (C/C++/Java)
	•	fingerprint/features
	•	Compare submissions (pairwise or batch) and produce:
	•	similarity score
	•	evidence (matched regions/line ranges)
	•	Store results tied to course + assignment + run.

App/UI responsibilities (thin wrapper):
	•	Instructor login + clicks buttons
	•	Displays results
	•	Calls engine API

No student login needed → students only interact via “submit with key”.

⸻

2) Model the workflow as objects first (multi-course + multi-assignment)

Minimum entities you should support:
	•	Instructor
	•	Course (e.g., COSC 4P02)
	•	Assignment (A1, A2, etc.)
	•	AssignmentKey (private “join key” per assignment)
	•	Submission (belongs to an assignment; created with valid key)
	•	Repository (where code is stored / committed snapshot)
	•	AnalysisRun (a “test run” the instructor triggers)
	•	ComparisonResult (score + evidence)

This automatically supports “multiple courses” and “separate key per assignment”.

⸻

3) Implement the key system early (it controls everything)

How it should behave
	•	Instructor creates an assignment → engine generates a private key.
	•	Student submits with that key → engine checks:
	•	key exists
	•	key belongs to that assignment
	•	key is active (not revoked/expired, optional)
	•	If key is fake/duplicate/invalid → reject.

Implementation detail (simple + strong)
	•	Store only a hash of the key (not the key itself).
	•	On submission, hash the provided key and compare.

This is a “security-ish” feature you can explain well in your documentation.

⸻

4) Repository + “commit when testing” (Agile-friendly interpretation)

What your prof is describing is basically: submissions are snapshots, and analysis runs operate on snapshots.

So define:
	•	A commit = a frozen version of an assignment repository at the moment you run detection.
	•	When instructor triggers “Run plagiarism check” → engine creates an AnalysisRun tied to the latest commit (or selected commit).

Agile vocabulary you can use (accurately):
	•	User story: “As an instructor, I want to generate an assignment key so only my students can submit.”
	•	Increment: implement key validation + basic ingestion first.
	•	Definition of Done: submission accepted only with valid key; stored; canonicalized; ready for analysis.

⸻

5) Canonicalization step (your prof’s “concatenate + strip comments”)

This becomes your pre-processing pipeline:

For each submission:
	1.	Collect all source files that match allowed extensions for that assignment.
	2.	Sort files deterministically (e.g., alphabetical path order).
	3.	Concatenate into one canonical string with clear separators, e.g.:
	•	// ===== FILE: path/to/X.java ===== (but note: you’ll strip comments—so make separator a non-comment delimiter like \n<<<FILE:path>>>\n)
	4.	Strip comments using language-aware rules.
	5.	Normalize whitespace (optional but recommended).
	6.	Output a single canonical “document” that goes to tokenization.

This is a huge win because it:
	•	standardizes multi-file projects
	•	reduces “noise”
	•	simplifies comparison

⸻

6) Tokenize (C/C++/Java) → fingerprint → compare

After canonicalization, the rest is consistent across languages:
	•	Tokenize into: keywords / identifiers / operators / literals / separators
	•	Optionally normalize identifiers and literals
	•	Build token k-grams → hashes/fingerprints
	•	Compute similarity:
	•	quick score (Jaccard on fingerprint sets)
	•	then evidence mapping for pairs above threshold

This is your “engine core.”

⸻

7) Support “ad-hoc” vs “full batch” runs

You’ll want two analysis modes:

Ad-hoc compare
	•	Instructor selects two submissions (or uploads two files)
	•	Engine returns score + evidence immediately

Batch run
	•	Instructor triggers run for an assignment
	•	Engine compares:
	•	all-vs-all within that assignment repository snapshot
	•	Outputs a ranked list of suspicious pairs

This matches what profs actually do.

⸻

8) Your “own API” endpoints (minimal but complete)

Even if you don’t build the full web app, define the engine interface like this:
	•	POST /courses
	•	POST /assignments → returns assignment_id + generated key (one-time display)
	•	POST /submissions (requires assignment_key)
	•	POST /analysis-runs (assignment_id + commit_id/latest)
	•	GET /analysis-runs/{id}/results
	•	POST /compare (ad-hoc: submission A vs B)
